    "modID": 2,
    "modName": "Personal Fall Risks"
    "info": [
        {
            "infoID": 1,
            "data": "Everyone’s health and lifestyle is different, which means your risk factors for a fall are also unique to you. Risk factors are often talked about as being intrinsic (internal to you) or extrinsic (environmental factors). We will do a quick review of some of these factors now and a deeper dive in later modules.",
            "listData": [
                {
                    "title": "Intrinsic Risk Factors",
                    "listItems": [
                        {
                            "title": "Physical Health",
                            "info": "There are a lot of ways physical health can impact your fall risk. Muscle strength and balance play important factors, as does any chronic conditions you might be managing."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Mental Health",
                            "info": "Research suggests that mental health conditions, like depression, mania and anxiety, and dementia, can increase your risk of falling. It is also suspected that social isolation can have a similar negative impact on falls risks."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Vision",
                            "info": "Unsurprising, changes in vision can put you at increased risk of falling. If you can’t see the crack in the sidewalk or the cord on the ground, you are at higher risk of tripping over them!"
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "History of Falling",
                            "info": "If you’ve fallen before, you are likely to fall again unless the underlying factors have been addressed. It can be hard to figure out those factors by yourself, so talk to your primary care provider about getting an assessment."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Pregnancy",
                            "info": "Pregnancy can increase your risk of falls, especially in the later trimesters. Pregnancy can change your center of balance as well as make it difficult to see where you are stepping!"
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Fear of Falling",
                            "info": "A fear of falling can cause a change in daily behaviors, unfortunately these changes often end up increasing an individual’s risk of falling rather than reducing it. If you notice you are changing behaviors or activities because you are afraid you will fall, it’s time to ask your primary care provider for a referral to an occupational therapist who can help you reduce fear by addressing the proper way to accomplish daily activities with less risk."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Age",
                            "info": "A fall can occur anytime during your life, but adults over the age of 60 are at highest risk for serious injury and fatality. As you get older, you don’t bounce as well as you did when you were young."
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "title": "Extrinsic Risk Factors",
                    "listItems": [
                        {
                            "title": "Home Layout and Organization",
                            "info": "From lighting and floor rugs to cords and clutter, the way our living space is organized can have a huge impact on your fall risk. The next module will go into these risks in more detail!"
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Walkability of Your Neighborhood ",
                            "info": "Walkability refers to how easy and safe it is to walk around a neighborhood. Sidewalks can improve walkability in a neighborhood, but if they are in poor condition or not cleaned in the winter, they can also be a fall risk."
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Medications",
                            "info": "From side effects to interactions between medications, the number and type of prescription and over-the-counter medications you take can impact your risk of falling. The module on Polypharmacy will dive deep into this topic!"
                        },
                        {
                            "title": "Footwear",
                            "info": "This may seem like a no brainer, like platform flip flops increase your risk, but picking out the right footwear for every occasion can help reduce your risks!"
                        }
